  "text": "Recent experiments on dynamic fracture of glass by Sharon and Fineberg [CITATION_1] have observed crack front deformations caused by surface imperfections that propagate for long distances. These involve both small amplitude corrugationswith a shape qualitatively similar to figure 2 -and much larger modulations of the crack velocity and the concomitant in-plane deformation of the crack front. Surprisingly, these pulses seem to propagate without appreciable attenuation and have a shape of the corrugations that is scale independent over more than an order of magnitude in length scale. The authors indicate that these and other features of their experiments suggest that the pulses have a soliton-like character indicative of the importance of non-linearities in spite of the small amplitude of the corrugations. Non-linear effects will in general involve both in-plane and outof-plane deformations. Via the existence of small dimensionless numbers such as ǫ(V ) and (c f − c h )/c R , where c f is the speed analogous to c R for in-plane waves [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , these could perhaps give rise to appreciable non-linear effects even with small amplitude corrugations. In any case, the observations provide clear evidence for the existence of crack front waves and suggest that non-linear interactions between them may be important at least in some regimes.",
